{# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
   FEATURES
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}
<section class="py-28 px-6" id="features">
  <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto">

    <div class="text-center mb-20">
      <div class="text-primary text-2xl mb-4 opacity-50" aria-hidden="true">✦</div>
      <h2 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-display glow-octarine mb-4">
        Spells in the Toolkit
      </h2>
      <p class="italic" style="color: oklch(55% 0.05 280);">
        "Every working wizard needs their tools — preferably ones that don't bite"
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">

      <div class="card bg-base-200 card-magical p-8">
        <div class="text-5xl mb-5" aria-hidden="true">🌙</div>
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-display mb-3" style="color: oklch(72% 0.26 135);">Lua-First Scripting</h3>
        <p class="leading-relaxed" style="color: oklch(78% 0.04 280);">
          All your game logic lives in Lua 5.4. The engine's C++ internals are there
          if you need them, but you probably won't. Hot-reload your scenes while the
          engine is running, and auto-generated EmmyLua stubs mean your editor knows
          what you're trying to type before you've quite finished typing it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="card bg-base-200 card-magical p-8">
        <div class="text-5xl mb-5" aria-hidden="true">⚡</div>
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-display mb-3" style="color: oklch(72% 0.26 135);">Archetype ECS</h3>
        <p class="leading-relaxed" style="color: oklch(78% 0.04 280);">
          An entity is just a number — a bare ID with no strong opinions about what
          it is. What it <em>does</em> depends entirely on its components. The archetype
          ECS stores each component type contiguously so systems only touch the data
          they actually need. There is no class hierarchy to inherit from, which most
          developers find to be a relief.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="card bg-base-200 card-magical p-8">
        <div class="text-5xl mb-5" aria-hidden="true">🔮</div>
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-display mb-3" style="color: oklch(72% 0.26 135);">Integrated ImGui Editor</h3>
        <p class="leading-relaxed" style="color: oklch(78% 0.04 280);">
          Think of it as a window into the running simulation. While the game is
          running you can inspect entities, edit their component values, and type
          Lua directly into a console. Frame times live in the profiler. The dockable
          layout remembers where you left things, which is more than most editors manage.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="card bg-base-200 card-magical p-8">
        <div class="text-5xl mb-5" aria-hidden="true">🌍</div>
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-display mb-3" style="color: oklch(72% 0.26 135);">Multi-Platform Shipping</h3>
        <p class="leading-relaxed" style="color: oklch(78% 0.04 280);">
          The same CMake project produces installers for Windows, archives for Linux,
          DMGs for macOS, and APKs for Android. SDL3 handles the platform differences;
          vcpkg handles the dependency graph without asking you to think about it.
          Four targets. One codebase. No port required.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>


